<chapter><title>Quick Reference</title>

<sect1><title>Opening a data set</title>
  <para>
    When the application is first run, you are presented with a skeleton window with File and Help menus. To open a
    data set, simply open the <command>File</command> menu and select open, as shown below.
  </para>

  <figure><title>View of the <command>GDMS</command> when first opened.</title>
    <execute><cmd>img</cmd><args>gdmsFirstOpen.png</args></execute>
  </figure>

  <para>
    While a data set is being loaded, a progress window appears.
  </para>

  <figure><title>Progress window.</title>
    <execute><cmd>img</cmd><args>gdmsProgess.png</args></execute>
  </figure>

  <para>
    Once the data set has been loaded, the application looks like:
  </para>

  <figure><title>A loaded data set. (mb_BUR1_GPS.DAT</title>
    <execute><cmd>img</cmd><args>gdmsData.png</args></execute>
  </figure>

</sect1>

<sect1><title>Saving a data set</title>
  <para>
     To save a data set after processing, select <command>File</command> -
     <command>Save</command>. The following window appears.
  </para>

   <figure><title>Save window.</title>
     <execute><cmd>img</cmd><args>gdmsSaveAs.png</args></execute>
   </figure>

  <para>
     Choose the desired location and file name and click <command>OK</command>.
  </para>
</sect1>

<sect1><title>Printing</title>
  <para>
    The <command>GDMS</command> offers standardard printing capabilities, including preview.
    To Print a data set, select <command>File</command> -
     <command>Print</command>. The following window appears.
  </para>

  <figure><title>Print window.</title>
     <execute><cmd>img</cmd><args>gdmsPrint.png</args></execute>
  </figure>

  <para>
    If not printing to file, the printer might need to be setup first. This is discussed in the
    next section.
  </para>

  <sect2><title>Print Setup</title>
    <para>
      The following figure shows the p[rinter setup window. To access printer setup, select,
      <command>File</command> - <command>Printer Setup</command>.
    </para>

    <figure><title>Printer Setup window.</title>
      <execute><cmd>img</cmd><args>gdmsPrintSetup.png</args></execute>
    </figure>

  </sect2>

  <sect2><title>Print Preview</title>
    <para>
      To preview the print job, select <command>File</command> - <command>Print Preiview</command>.
    </para>
  </sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1><title>Configuring the User Interface</title>
  <para>
    The look and feel of the user interface can be configured to suit individual users. Please refer to the configuration
    chapter for full details on this feature.
  </para>
</sect1>

<sect1><title>Data Analysis</title>
  <para>
    The following items are all found in the Maths menu. The menu is shown below.
  </para>

  <figure><title>Maths menu.</title>
     <execute><cmd>img</cmd><args>gdmsMaths</args></execute>
   </figure>


  <sect2><title>Time Domain Analysis</title>
  <para>
    Ba Ba Black sheep have you any wool, yes sir yes sir 3 bags full..
    But you can't have it because in case you haven't noticed, there's a drought on.
  </para>

    <sect3><title>Least Squeares</title>
      <para>
        The available options in the least squares menu are Variance Co-variance and Random Walk.
      </para>
    </sect3> 
  </sect2>

  <sect2><title>Interpolation</title>
    <para>
       The available options in the Interpolation menu are Nearest neighbour, linear interpolation, natural spline,
       cubic spline and divided differences.
    </para>
  </sect2>

  <sect2><title>Windowing data</title>
    <para>
      The available options in the Windowing menu are Blackman, Chebychev, Hamming, Hanning and rectangular.
    </para>
  </sect2>


  <sect2><title>Frequency Domain Analysis</title>
    <para>
      Select the Maths menu, select Fast Fourier Transform or PSD plot. Note, before successfully carrying out
      operations in the frequency domain, the data must be interpolated and windowed.
    </para>
  </sect2>

</sect1>

</chapter>

